<i class="categories">blogging :: software :: python ::
twisted</i><br/><br/><p/><br /><a
href="http://www.advogato.org/person/oubiwann/">Advogato</a> has served me
well over the past year, and I will continue to use it for blogging. I email a
special account on one of my servers with my blog entries, and it gets
published within seconds on <a
href="http://www.advogato.org/person/oubiwann/">Advogato</a>. I have nightly
cronjobs that run XML-RPC queries against <a
href="http://www.advogato.org/person/oubiwann/">Advogato</a> and save backups
(in addition to the originals which are in my "Sent" folder). This makes me
very happy, as I suffered a traumatic server crash over a year ago, wherein I
lost over a year's worth of world-changing blog posts.<br /><br />However, I
believe I am ready to take blogging back into my own hands. I managed to
rescue some of the data on the drive, including early posts from 2003 and part
of 2004. These are currently archived <a
href="http://olded.crossrodes.org/">here</a>, but I would like to unify all
old posts, <a href="http://www.advogato.org/person/oubiwann/">Advogato</a>
posts, and future posts in a single framework, look-and-feel.<br /><br />As a
result, I have finally broken down and started writing a collection of
user-land networked applications: <br /><ul> <li><a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcImageDBScreens
hots">ImageDB</a>, a small web micro-app which provides a backend upon which
one could write an image gallery application like <a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcPyKon">this on
e</a><a href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcPyKon"
></a>; uses image-tagging like <a
href="http://del.icio.us/oubiwann">del.icio.us</a>;</li> <li><a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcAccountsDB">Ac
countsDB</a>, which will provide distributed user and group management,
authentication, as well as fine-grained permissioning with ACLs (access
control lists) and ACL management for applications;</li> <li><a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcMessageDB">Mes
sageDB</a>, which will store and index <a
href="http://www.faqs.org/rfcs/rfc2822.html">RFC 2822</a>-compliant messages,
will allow users to tag them like <a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcImageDBScreens
hots">ImageDB</a> and <a href="http://del.icio.us/oubiwann">del.icio.us</a>,
as well as providing many convenient means for users and parent applications
to add messages;<br /> </li> <li><a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcWeBlog">WeBlog
</a>, which will be composed of the micro-applications <a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcMessageDB">Mes
sageDB</a>, <a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcAccountsDB">Ac
countsDB</a>, and <a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcImageDBScreens
hots">ImageDB</a> and provide a nice user interface for blog posts, blogs, and
groups of blogs (community spaces).</li> </ul> This is just a handful of the
full suite we are working on <a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection">here</a>.<br /><br
/>All of these applications are small, networked, light-weight, and run
independently of heavy software like Apache, MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc. They are
<a href="http://python.org/">python</a>- and <a
href="http://twistedmatrix.com/">twisted</a>-powered. We have plans of
implementing peering (using <a
href="http://www.divmod.org/users/glyph/q2qpresentation.pdf">Q2Q</a>/<a href="
http://divmod.org/trac/wiki/DivmodVertex">Vertex</a>) so that, for example, a
trusted network of <a
href="http://projects.adytum.us/tracs/TwistedCollection/wiki/AtcImageDBScreens
hots">ImageDB</a> installations could provide images for each other (like a
private, distributed, images.google.com). There are so many possible ways that
this could go, it's just insanely exciting. We're talking new paradigm here,
folks.<br /><br />So, stay tuned. This blog-space and my account on <a
href="http://www.advogato.org/person/oubiwann/">Advogato</a> will eventually
become re-publishers of ElectricDuncan running on WeBlog ;-) And then I'll
have two more backups of these techno-babble ramblings...